'''Vivisection''' (from [[Latin]] ''vivus'' ("alive") + ''sectio'' ("cutting")) is a doing a [[surgery]] as an experiment on a living [[organism]], usually animals. It is sometimes used to mean [[animal testing]] itself (see [[Animal testing#Definitions|animal testing]]).<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/ebc/article-9382118?query=Vivisection&ct= "Vivisection"], ''Encyclopaedia Britannica'', 2009: "Vivisection: operation on a living animal for experimental rather than healing purposes; more broadly, all experimentation on live animals."</ref><ref name=Tansey>Tansey, E.M. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1139874/pdf/medhist00063-0114.pdf Review of ''Vivisection in Historical Perspective by Nicholaas A. Rupke], book reviews, National Center for Biotechnology Information, p. 226.</ref><ref>Croce, Pietro. ''Vivisection or Science? An Investigation into Testing Drugs and Safeguarding Health''. Zed Books, 1999, and [http://www.buav.org/aboutus "About Us"], British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection.</ref> The word is often used by people or organizations who dislike animal experimentation<ref>Yarri, Donna. [http://books.google.com/books?id=DkNJXIWbhtEC&pg=PA163&lpg=PA163&dq=vivisection+pejorative+not+used&source=bl&ots=LPpIiQKFgm&sig=WF-ZfeTc27E6Gpw9z1sPKvM3Jkk&hl=en&ei=dWTgSv66BY6zlAeUlNSEDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CAwQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=vivisection%20pejorative%20not%20used&f=false ''The Ethics of Animal Experimentation: A Critical Analysis and Constructive Christian Proposal], Oxford University Press, 2005, p. 163.</ref>

